WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:04.040
Welcome everyone to today's major symposium on

2
00:00:04.140 --> 00:00:05.360
extrachromosomal DNA.

3
00:00:06.940 --> 00:00:08.900
It's a huge pleasure to chair this session.

4
00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:13.610
My name is Anton Henson. I'm a physician scientist from Berlin, and it's really a

5
00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:17.300
pleasure to do this session together with my co-speakers, Peter Lai

6
00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:19.000
and Howard Chang, who

7
00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:21.220
have really shaped our view

8
00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:24.580
on ecDNA over the past couple of years.

9
00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:27.800
I'm waiting for slide. Yeah.

10
00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:32.259
So the session is called Beyond Chromosomes, Mechanisms, Consequences,

11
00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:35.560
and Therapeutic Opportunities of Extrachromosomal DNA.

12
00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:38.900
And I'd like to start this with an overview, a very simple one,

13
00:00:39.880 --> 00:00:41.080
with basically two cells.

14
00:00:42.870 --> 00:00:46.540
They are both dividing, and one of them is following the

15
00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:49.720
classical rules of inheritance and the other is not.

16
00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:54.280
As you can see on the right, extrachromosomal DNA

17
00:00:55.100 --> 00:00:58.960
violates one of the most fundamental principles of inheritance

18
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.580
during mitosis, in that it distributes randomly to daughter cells,

19
00:01:03.440 --> 00:01:07.420
and through that process is able to fuel intracellular

20
00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:10.680
variance in a way that is otherwise not possible.

21
00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:14.990
And we'll hear today how we can not only observe this now in cells,

22
00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:18.740
but we can measure it at scale and using

23
00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:22.410
some new algorithms that Howard will talk about.

24
00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:30.420
And we now know that extrachromosomal DNA is not a rare event.

25
00:01:30.460 --> 00:01:33.640
It's actually something that we can observe across different cancers in adult

26
00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:37.620
cancers and pediatrics alike. And this is a figure from a review

27
00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:41.320
that came out two days ago in "Cell," as part of a special

28
00:01:41.420 --> 00:01:45.370
issue on the hallmarks of cancers that was written by Howard, Paul, and others

29
00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:45.980
in the field

30
00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:50.660
that really shows you how widely we can find ecDNA nowadays.

31
00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:56.460
But we also come to realize that ecDNA is a moving target.

32
00:01:56.520 --> 00:01:59.950
It's quite dynamic. There are catastrophic events that can lead to their

33
00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:01.040
generation.

34
00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:06.700
Many structural variants occur, and you'll see tomorrow a talk on ecDNA

35
00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:07.360
fusions.

36
00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:12.080
And all of this really leads to quite disrupted oncogene

37
00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:12.640
expression.

38
00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:16.540
And we're also learning more and more on the inheritance

39
00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:20.440
patterns, as you'll see later. All of this

40
00:02:20.540 --> 00:02:24.320
just contributes to how ecDNA drives

41
00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:25.080
tumor progression.

42
00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:27.000
And

43
00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:29.160
all of this

44
00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:33.880
really shows how it touches on so many different parts of the hallmarks of cancer.

45
00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:36.960
And so we believe that ecDNA is really

46
00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:40.560
a systems-level driver of cancer.

47
00:02:42.420 --> 00:02:45.640
But in order to do so, it needs to actually be maintained in a cell.

48
00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:49.900
And so you'll hear from Howard Chang on how certain retention

49
00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:53.049
elements guarantee that ecDNA are retained within the cell.

50
00:02:54.180 --> 00:02:58.060
In my talk, I'll talk to you about what happens when this doesn't go right

51
00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:01.880
and when ecDNA leaves the nucleus and goes into micronuclei.

52
00:03:04.060 --> 00:03:06.410
In Peter Lai's talk, you'll actually hear about

53
00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:10.460
how this is not the end of the story and how micronuclei

54
00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:15.060
can be transferred from one cell to the next through cell-to-cell

55
00:03:15.180 --> 00:03:15.670
contacts.

56
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:20.560
So you'll really get a snapshot today on different parts of a life cycle of an

57
00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:21.670
extrachromosomal DNA.

58
00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:26.700
And at the end, we'll also touch on how this is relevant clinically and how we

59
00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:28.500
might go about this therapeutically.

60
00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:33.420
So with this, I'd like to introduce the first speaker of today, Peter Lai

61
00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:36.079
from UT Southwestern. Thank you, Peter.

62
00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:45.460
All right. Thank you very much to the organizers and to Anton for chairing this

63
00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:45.940
session.

64
00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:52.200
Okay, so my name is Peter Lai, and today I'm going to talk to you about some

65
00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:55.860
emerging work from my lab which is currently unpublished, but hopefully, will

66
00:03:55.900 --> 00:03:58.520
be published within the next month or so.

67
00:03:58.540 --> 00:04:02.120
And so my laboratory is generally interested in the mechanisms and consequences of

68
00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:04.600
genomic instability in the context of cancer development.

69
00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:09.320
And so today I'm going to tell you about a catastrophic process that can give rise

70
00:04:09.329 --> 00:04:11.800
to extrachromosomal DNAs or ecDNAs.

71
00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:16.360
And so this is commonly referred to as chromothripsis, which is a Greek term for

72
00:04:16.459 --> 00:04:20.320
chromosome shattering. And this was discovered by cancer genome sequencing

73
00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:24.360
efforts over a decade ago. And so what they had initially

74
00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:28.240
hypothesized from the current models of chromothripsis is that you start off

75
00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:31.720
with an intact chromosome that undergoes some type of chromosome shattering event

76
00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:35.220
to give rise to a number of different chromosome

77
00:04:35.260 --> 00:04:39.040
fragments. These chromosome fragments are then subsequently repaired by the

78
00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:42.940
cell's intrinsic DNA repair machinery and then put back together in the wrong order

79
00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:46.479
to generate a derivative chromosome that's characterized by complex

80
00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:50.490
rearrangements with segments that are now juxtaposed next to

81
00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:52.570
segments that don't normally appear next to each other.

82
00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:57.160
Some of these fragments also fail to participate in the religation event and also

83
00:04:57.400 --> 00:05:00.820
can become lost to the cell and of a particular importance to this

84
00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:04.840
session, some of these fragments can also circularize to give rise to

85
00:05:04.900 --> 00:05:08.670
extrachromosomal DNA elements that we all know can harbor oncogenes and

86
00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:10.280
genes that confer drug resistance.

87
00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:14.620
And so typically from whole genome sequencing, the way that we would interpret

88
00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:15.380
these types of

89
00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:18.640
events is by looking at these copy number plots.

90
00:05:18.980 --> 00:05:22.060
So this is an example where one chromosome is plotted from one end of the

91
00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:25.820
chromosome to the other end, for a diploid chromosome sits at a copy number state

92
00:05:25.860 --> 00:05:26.140
of two.

93
00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:30.240
And after a chromothripsis event, you would now see a number of structural variants

94
00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:33.900
that connects random pieces of the chromosome together, and this can also result in

95
00:05:33.960 --> 00:05:37.390
loss of copy numbers when fragments are deleted, as well as

96
00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:41.120
extrachromosomal DNA elements that get amplified to tens to hundreds of copies.

97
00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:45.320
And this is a very simplistic overview of how we can see these events, and here's

98
00:05:45.340 --> 00:05:49.280
one example from the original chromothripsis paper from Peter Campbell and

99
00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:53.180
colleagues back in 2011. And so in this example, you can see a

100
00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:56.220
chromothripsis event affecting chromosome 5, in which there are

101
00:05:57.100 --> 00:06:00.680
a number of structural variants that connects different parts of the chromosome

102
00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:04.440
together, probably about a couple dozen here or so, as well as

103
00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:08.040
an oscillation in DNA copy number state in which it oscillates back and forth

104
00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:11.740
between regions of the chromosome that are retained in this top copy number state

105
00:06:11.750 --> 00:06:14.790
and then regions of the chromosome that are deleted from this bottom copy number

106
00:06:14.860 --> 00:06:18.480
state. And if we zoom out and take a look at this particular example

107
00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:22.340
in a genome-wide view, we can see that chromothripsis for this particular

108
00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:25.600
chromosome is the sole site of genetic abnormality, which really raised the

109
00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:28.400
question of how do these events arise

110
00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:32.420
on a specific chromosome, whereas the rest of the genome is practically

111
00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:35.974
spared?And so shortly after the discovery of

112
00:06:36.024 --> 00:06:37.344
chromothripsis, several groups

113
00:06:38.204 --> 00:06:42.184
began to propose that chromosome segregation defects during mitosis could be one

114
00:06:42.224 --> 00:06:44.164
initiating event in driving chromothripsis.

115
00:06:44.504 --> 00:06:47.124
So here's an example of a cell entering mitosis.

116
00:06:47.544 --> 00:06:51.304
Chromosomes are aligned at the metaphase plate, and one particular chromosome is

117
00:06:51.344 --> 00:06:53.564
now missegregated and improperly aligned.

118
00:06:53.854 --> 00:06:57.564
And when this cell enters anaphase, this chromosome now gets missegregated into

119
00:06:57.584 --> 00:07:00.084
this abnormal nuclear structure called the micronucleus.

120
00:07:00.444 --> 00:07:03.844
And this was a very attractive hypothesis for chromothripsis at the time because

121
00:07:03.884 --> 00:07:07.724
now you can spatially isolate a single chromosome away from the primary genome,

122
00:07:08.084 --> 00:07:10.624
where it presumably acquires DNA damage.

123
00:07:11.074 --> 00:07:14.664
And indeed, in 2015, David Pelman and colleagues combined live cell

124
00:07:14.684 --> 00:07:18.634
imaging with single-cell DNA sequencing to demonstrate that the daughter cells

125
00:07:18.644 --> 00:07:22.594
from a mother cell with a micronucleus can in fact acquire the signatures of

126
00:07:22.604 --> 00:07:25.004
chromothripsis that we see in cancer genomes.

127
00:07:25.824 --> 00:07:29.484
Of particular importance to this session, they also detected the

128
00:07:29.524 --> 00:07:33.224
presence of circular DNA structures from single-cell DNA sequencing data.

129
00:07:33.624 --> 00:07:37.504
And at the time, it was sort of unclear whether these represented bona fide

130
00:07:37.544 --> 00:07:41.204
ecDNAs or double minute chromosomes, and whether they were stably

131
00:07:41.464 --> 00:07:42.903
maintained within these genomes.

132
00:07:44.504 --> 00:07:48.324
So my group has established a method to study

133
00:07:48.364 --> 00:07:51.954
mechanisms underlying chromothripsis using a targeted chromothripsis approach in

134
00:07:51.984 --> 00:07:55.824
which we can induce the missegregation of a specific human chromosome into

135
00:07:55.864 --> 00:07:57.654
micronuclei at very high frequency.

136
00:07:58.074 --> 00:08:00.904
And so I won't go into the details on how this works, but essentially we can take

137
00:08:00.964 --> 00:08:04.764
human DLD1 colon cancer cells, and we can turn off the Y chromosome

138
00:08:04.844 --> 00:08:07.244
centromere using this combination of these two drugs.

139
00:08:07.664 --> 00:08:11.524
And so when we add doxycycline and auxin to these cells, the Y centromere is

140
00:08:11.564 --> 00:08:14.904
turned off, and now we have an enrichment of these Y chromosome-specific

141
00:08:14.964 --> 00:08:17.534
micronuclei that we can detect by DNA FISH.

142
00:08:19.404 --> 00:08:23.284
Additionally, if we now propagate clones after inducing its

143
00:08:23.304 --> 00:08:26.844
formation into micronuclei, we can see that under control conditions, this is what

144
00:08:26.884 --> 00:08:28.504
a normal Y chromosome would look like.

145
00:08:28.874 --> 00:08:32.084
And I forgot to mention that we also use CRISPR editing to insert a selection

146
00:08:32.124 --> 00:08:35.824
marker specifically into the Y chromosome, and it's positioned here.

147
00:08:36.084 --> 00:08:38.725
And after a chromothripsis event, this is now what it would look like.

148
00:08:38.804 --> 00:08:42.494
So you would have a series of rearrangements as well as copy number changes

149
00:08:42.824 --> 00:08:46.204
that's very reminiscent of what we typically see in human cancers.

150
00:08:47.444 --> 00:08:51.404
Here's another example of clones that we can derive in which we see that the

151
00:08:51.444 --> 00:08:55.344
cell essentially lost the entire Y chromosome except for

152
00:08:55.364 --> 00:08:58.784
this particular fragment that sits right at the position where the neomycin

153
00:08:58.844 --> 00:09:02.764
resistance gene is located. And so it's now amplified to a higher copy

154
00:09:02.804 --> 00:09:05.244
number state, and if we use DNA

155
00:09:06.404 --> 00:09:10.364
probes to look at these on mitotic chromosomes, we can see indeed that they are

156
00:09:10.424 --> 00:09:14.124
now localized to ecDNAs, and they also become amplified

157
00:09:15.804 --> 00:09:19.324
manyfold within these cells. And by whole genome sequencing, we can also

158
00:09:19.424 --> 00:09:23.364
reconstruct the sequence of these events in which this

159
00:09:23.424 --> 00:09:26.824
ecDNA, which is about 900 kilobases in size, was

160
00:09:26.864 --> 00:09:30.804
originated from the ligation of two distinct fragments derived from the Y

161
00:09:30.824 --> 00:09:32.614
chromosome at this particular location.

162
00:09:32.924 --> 00:09:36.804
So this was the first experimental evidence that a chromothripsis event mediated

163
00:09:36.844 --> 00:09:40.744
by micronuclei can in fact give rise to stable ecDNAs that can then

164
00:09:40.764 --> 00:09:42.464
become propagated and amplified.

165
00:09:44.244 --> 00:09:47.384
So using the system that I had just described to you, another cool thing about it

166
00:09:47.424 --> 00:09:50.644
is that we can now look at mitotic chromosomes right after we induce

167
00:09:50.684 --> 00:09:54.484
micronuclei, and we can recapitulate the sequence of events that leads to

168
00:09:54.504 --> 00:09:58.454
chromothripsis. In this example, this is a Y chromosome that had now shattered into

169
00:09:58.484 --> 00:10:02.344
multiple fragments, and you can see the fragments here lit up

170
00:10:02.384 --> 00:10:05.734
by the green FISH probes. And we've used this system now to make several

171
00:10:05.734 --> 00:10:07.864
discoveries about how chromothripsis arises.

172
00:10:07.904 --> 00:10:11.824
For example, under-replicated chromosomes typically undergo mitotic cleavage by

173
00:10:11.864 --> 00:10:15.764
this SLX4-XPF-ERCC1 endonuclease to shatter

174
00:10:15.844 --> 00:10:17.644
or fragment the chromosome during mitosis.

175
00:10:18.034 --> 00:10:18.374
And once the

176
00:10:19.604 --> 00:10:23.164
chromosome has fragmented, these fragments are now held together by this protein

177
00:10:23.204 --> 00:10:26.654
complex, and they segregate asymmetrically via this

178
00:10:26.844 --> 00:10:30.833
clustering mechanism. However, some of these fragments can also fail to participate

179
00:10:30.864 --> 00:10:34.844
in this clustering and also mislocalize to the cytoplasm at the exit

180
00:10:34.864 --> 00:10:35.604
of mitosis.

181
00:10:36.534 --> 00:10:40.194
And so one question that graduate student Liz Murray wanted to ask in my

182
00:10:40.264 --> 00:10:44.014
laboratory is, beyond generating cell-intrinsic genomic alterations and

183
00:10:44.084 --> 00:10:47.724
rearrangements, can micronuclei also impact nearby

184
00:10:47.784 --> 00:10:51.704
cells? And so to address this, she started with RPE1 cells,

185
00:10:51.743 --> 00:10:53.243
which are non-transformed cells.

186
00:10:53.623 --> 00:10:57.304
She labeled DNA with the fluorescent dye called SirDNA and then

187
00:10:57.344 --> 00:11:00.784
induced micronucleation using a combination of mitotic inhibitors.

188
00:11:01.244 --> 00:11:03.504
And so I'm going to let this video play, and you're going to see the cells moving

189
00:11:03.584 --> 00:11:07.214
around as cells normally do. And what really caught our attention is that

190
00:11:07.264 --> 00:11:10.734
oftentimes these cells would form these long-stretched protrusions between these

191
00:11:10.764 --> 00:11:14.684
two adjacent cells. And if we look at the DNA stain, we can see the presence of

192
00:11:14.724 --> 00:11:18.714
this DNA stain that seemingly passages through this tube-like connection.

193
00:11:19.224 --> 00:11:22.054
And although we didn't really understand at the time when we saw this what exactly

194
00:11:22.084 --> 00:11:25.624
those were, looking in the literature, these are now referred to as tunneling

195
00:11:25.634 --> 00:11:29.344
nanotubes, which have been described in a variety of physiological and disease

196
00:11:29.384 --> 00:11:29.924
contexts.

197
00:11:30.884 --> 00:11:34.664
And these tunneling nanotubes typically transport various types of cytoplasmic

198
00:11:34.684 --> 00:11:38.304
cargo, including proteins, organelles, and RNA.

199
00:11:38.404 --> 00:11:41.834
But whether DNA can serve as a substrate for transfer has not been

200
00:11:41.844 --> 00:11:45.464
demonstrated. And if this was correct, this would sort of serve as the first

201
00:11:45.504 --> 00:11:48.664
experimental evidence of a horizontal gene transfer-like mechanism

202
00:11:49.604 --> 00:11:51.984
that's occurring in human cells.

203
00:11:53.904 --> 00:11:57.464
In order to better visualize this, we wanted to arrest the cells from

204
00:11:57.474 --> 00:11:59.594
migration and to stop moving around.

205
00:11:59.604 --> 00:12:02.984
So we added this cytochalasin D, which is an actin inhibitor.

206
00:12:02.994 --> 00:12:06.144
And when we do this, the cells immediately begin to constrict, and what really

207
00:12:06.184 --> 00:12:09.924
caught our attention was that the cells that had already formed nanotubes continue

208
00:12:09.944 --> 00:12:12.704
to maintain those nanotubes, such as here.

209
00:12:13.054 --> 00:12:15.664
And if you look closely, you could also see the transport of these bulky

210
00:12:15.674 --> 00:12:19.314
cytoplasmic cargo between these two adjacent cells between these nanotubes.

211
00:12:19.714 --> 00:12:23.654
And if we now take the cells and fix them at a particular time and then

212
00:12:23.684 --> 00:12:27.624
stain them for microtubules, we can see that these nanotubes are comprised of

213
00:12:27.664 --> 00:12:31.414
different components of the mammalian cytoskeleton that forms this sort of

214
00:12:31.444 --> 00:12:33.574
intricate network between cells in

215
00:12:33.584 --> 00:12:37.284
culture.So now we combine these different

216
00:12:37.304 --> 00:12:39.544
conditions together, and we can include

217
00:12:41.084 --> 00:12:44.184
this DNA dye, and we can also induce micronuclei formation.

218
00:12:44.524 --> 00:12:48.204
And we can indeed see the presence of these SIRH DNA labeled DNAs

219
00:12:48.244 --> 00:12:50.654
passaging through these nanotube-like structures.

220
00:12:50.664 --> 00:12:53.924
And from measuring the speed of this transfer, it seems to be

221
00:12:54.184 --> 00:12:58.044
consistent with the transport of bulky cargo by molecular motors.

222
00:12:58.644 --> 00:13:02.184
Additionally, these events are stimulated by induction of mitotic errors.

223
00:13:02.424 --> 00:13:06.344
And importantly, these nanotubes are not induced by genomic instability or

224
00:13:06.424 --> 00:13:09.884
having the micronuclei. So they form essentially spontaneously from direct

225
00:13:09.924 --> 00:13:10.864
cell-cell contact.

226
00:13:11.864 --> 00:13:15.084
And so now we're no longer going to use the cytoclazin D, so we can look at cells

227
00:13:15.094 --> 00:13:19.024
in their intact native state. And if we take these cells and we stain them for the

228
00:13:19.044 --> 00:13:22.444
cytoskeletal markers, tubulin and actin, we can see these stretched protrusions

229
00:13:22.464 --> 00:13:26.144
between these cells. And if we use a different DNA stain called YoYo1, we can see

230
00:13:26.184 --> 00:13:29.544
this large bulky micronucleus or piece of DNA

231
00:13:29.964 --> 00:13:33.764
trapped here between these two tubes, or between these two cells within this

232
00:13:33.804 --> 00:13:37.584
tube. And so what we think is happening is that a

233
00:13:37.604 --> 00:13:41.544
genomically unstable cell with micronuclei could potentially

234
00:13:41.604 --> 00:13:45.224
form nanotubes connections with these recipient cells, where the DNA can then

235
00:13:45.244 --> 00:13:48.604
passage through this nanotube if the DNA was present in the cytoplasm.

236
00:13:49.364 --> 00:13:53.084
And in order to really test this, we began to label distinct population of cells

237
00:13:53.104 --> 00:13:56.544
with different markers. So here we're taking one set of cells, and we're labeling

238
00:13:56.584 --> 00:14:00.044
them with histone H2B-GFP and another set with histone

239
00:14:00.164 --> 00:14:03.564
H2B-RFP in red. And so now we can combine these two

240
00:14:03.604 --> 00:14:07.174
cells together in co-culture experiments and then

241
00:14:07.604 --> 00:14:10.704
perform microscopy. And what you're going to see is a green micronucleus at the

242
00:14:10.744 --> 00:14:14.444
bottom of the screen coming up, and it's going to transfer over to that cell with a

243
00:14:14.464 --> 00:14:18.324
red nucleus. And so the two cells now migrate apart, and it seems that this green

244
00:14:18.404 --> 00:14:21.224
piece of DNA is now part of this red cell.

245
00:14:21.824 --> 00:14:24.744
And so these were examples of DNA transfer between

246
00:14:24.804 --> 00:14:28.284
the same RPE1 to RPE1 cell.

247
00:14:28.824 --> 00:14:31.034
And now we can also do this in very different contexts.

248
00:14:31.124 --> 00:14:33.024
We can take cells derived from the kidney.

249
00:14:33.074 --> 00:14:37.024
So these are renal proximal tubule epithelial cells cultured

250
00:14:37.084 --> 00:14:40.024
with RPE1 cells, so derived from different tissues.

251
00:14:40.394 --> 00:14:43.844
And we also see these similar types of intercellular DNA transfer events,

252
00:14:44.483 --> 00:14:46.993
suggesting that they're not restricted to individual cell types.

253
00:14:48.244 --> 00:14:52.034
Next, in order to see this in a little bit more detail, we also labeled the

254
00:14:52.044 --> 00:14:55.324
plasma membrane using this CAAX targeting motif

255
00:14:56.184 --> 00:14:59.644
labeled with a halo tag. And so here you can see this long, stretched thin

256
00:14:59.684 --> 00:15:01.504
protrusion between these two different cells.

257
00:15:01.824 --> 00:15:05.814
And then now you can see the presence of this H2B-GFP labeled chromatin moving

258
00:15:05.844 --> 00:15:09.644
from this donor cell to this RFP labeled recipient

259
00:15:09.724 --> 00:15:09.914
cell.

260
00:15:13.304 --> 00:15:17.244
We see this, and so after the DNA transfers, if we were then to

261
00:15:17.264 --> 00:15:20.084
fix the cells, this is sort of what it would look like.

262
00:15:20.124 --> 00:15:23.984
So these are examples of what we refer to as mismatched labeling

263
00:15:24.024 --> 00:15:25.924
between the nuclei and micronuclei.

264
00:15:26.314 --> 00:15:29.984
And so here, for example, is a kidney epithelial

265
00:15:30.064 --> 00:15:33.884
cell labeled with histone H2B mCherry in which its nucleus is

266
00:15:33.944 --> 00:15:37.884
red. And now it harbors this micronucleus or a fragment of DNA

267
00:15:37.944 --> 00:15:41.484
that presumably arose from a neighboring kidney cell

268
00:15:41.524 --> 00:15:45.113
expressing H2B-GFP. And we can see this also under very different

269
00:15:45.124 --> 00:15:48.494
conditions. So for example, if we induce micronuclei using

270
00:15:48.904 --> 00:15:52.484
depletion of mitotic checkpoint proteins to inactivate the mitotic

271
00:15:52.504 --> 00:15:54.654
checkpoint, we can also do this and

272
00:15:55.924 --> 00:15:58.893
arrest the cells in mitosis for a brief period using a

273
00:15:59.844 --> 00:16:03.544
microtubule polymerization inhibitor, and then

274
00:16:03.584 --> 00:16:06.584
release them from this arrest and allow them to form mitotic errors.

275
00:16:06.864 --> 00:16:09.384
And we can also see similar types of DNA transfer events.

276
00:16:10.884 --> 00:16:13.324
Additionally, this is not limited to just mitotic errors.

277
00:16:13.364 --> 00:16:17.264
So if we induce DNA damage using variety of means,

278
00:16:17.284 --> 00:16:20.814
so for example, if we use Cas9 to induce a DNA double strand break

279
00:16:20.944 --> 00:16:24.564
specifically on the short arm of chromosome 3, this would generate chromosome

280
00:16:24.724 --> 00:16:28.604
3p containing micronuclei. And we can also see similar types of DNA

281
00:16:28.644 --> 00:16:31.804
transfer events between these co-cultured and

282
00:16:32.324 --> 00:16:36.244
distinctly labeled cells. We can also hit cells with ionizing radiation to

283
00:16:36.284 --> 00:16:39.904
induce DNA damage on a genome-wide level and also induce

284
00:16:40.744 --> 00:16:44.324
DNA transfer. And then just to give you a sense of how often this

285
00:16:44.364 --> 00:16:47.374
occurs, this is one way that we've begun to measure

286
00:16:48.724 --> 00:16:52.264
this. So here we're taking RPE1 cells, treat them up with mitotic inhibitors.

287
00:16:52.604 --> 00:16:56.344
And under these conditions, approximately 30% of cells has at least one

288
00:16:56.384 --> 00:17:00.144
micronucleus. And if we now look at all of those micronuclei and ask what

289
00:17:00.224 --> 00:17:04.204
fraction have this mismatched labeling, about 4% of those have a mismatched

290
00:17:04.214 --> 00:17:07.704
label, suggesting that DNA transfer occurs at a low yet

291
00:17:07.844 --> 00:17:10.964
measurable rate across many different cell types, many different

292
00:17:10.984 --> 00:17:14.325
conditions. And it's also dependent on cell-to-cell contact.

293
00:17:14.464 --> 00:17:18.024
So for example, if we culture cells and we reduce the density of cell

294
00:17:18.045 --> 00:17:21.884
culture in order to prevent direct cell-cell contact, we can essentially

295
00:17:21.924 --> 00:17:25.844
eliminate this event. And if we also use a filter to block the two different cells

296
00:17:25.884 --> 00:17:29.664
from coming into direct contact, we can also inhibit DNA transfer.

297
00:17:31.584 --> 00:17:35.484
So after the DNA goes into the recipient cell, it makes its way into the cytoplasm,

298
00:17:35.564 --> 00:17:39.054
and we next wondered what happens to that piece of DNA after

299
00:17:39.104 --> 00:17:40.244
that. So when the

300
00:17:41.084 --> 00:17:44.614
recipient cell with the transferred DNA fragment enters the next mitosis,

301
00:17:44.944 --> 00:17:48.284
its nuclear envelope disassembles, and the chromosomes begin to condense.

302
00:17:48.764 --> 00:17:51.794
And what we see is that the transferred DNA fragments here labeled in different

303
00:17:51.864 --> 00:17:53.654
colors from the native chromosomes

304
00:17:55.664 --> 00:17:59.524
essentially rejoins the host chromosomes during mitosis, and they

305
00:17:59.544 --> 00:18:03.424
can either be aligned with the host chromosomes, for example, here are examples

306
00:18:03.484 --> 00:18:07.244
from metaphase as well as anaphase, or they can also be misaligned

307
00:18:07.704 --> 00:18:11.564
as well. And so these are essentially fragments of DNA that either

308
00:18:11.584 --> 00:18:14.104
contain or do not contain a human centromere.

309
00:18:15.824 --> 00:18:19.064
So after it reincorporates into the host genome, the next question we wanted to ask

310
00:18:19.124 --> 00:18:22.264
was whether these events can give rise to stable and functional

311
00:18:24.084 --> 00:18:26.604
DNAs within that recipient cell population.

312
00:18:27.024 --> 00:18:30.684
And so to test this, we went back to that system that I had described earlier in

313
00:18:30.704 --> 00:18:34.204
which we can turn off the Y chromosome centromere and induce its formation in a

314
00:18:34.244 --> 00:18:38.064
micronuclei. And then just to remind you, we also use CRISPR editing to

315
00:18:38.124 --> 00:18:41.344
insert a neomycin resistance marker into this chromosome.

316
00:18:41.664 --> 00:18:45.644
And so now the experiment that we really wanted to do was ask if we co-culture male

317
00:18:45.764 --> 00:18:48.444
cells with Y chromosome containing this selection marker

318
00:18:49.324 --> 00:18:52.844
in a micronucleus with female cells, can the female cells

319
00:18:53.004 --> 00:18:56.934
eventually take up fragments of the Y chromosome and become resistant to the

320
00:18:57.004 --> 00:18:58.004
drug that

321
00:18:58.824 --> 00:19:01.364
this selection marker confers resistance

322
00:19:01.404 --> 00:19:05.196
to?And so to test this, we performed a

323
00:19:05.236 --> 00:19:07.936
series of experiments, and it's a little bit complicated, but I'm going to try to

324
00:19:07.976 --> 00:19:11.236
walk you through it. And so here we took these male donor cells with the

325
00:19:11.396 --> 00:19:13.836
Y-encoded neomycin resistance gene.

326
00:19:14.116 --> 00:19:17.696
These cells are labeled in green, and we co-cultured these with female recipient

327
00:19:17.736 --> 00:19:21.616
cells with a different set of selection markers and also a different fluorophore.

328
00:19:21.656 --> 00:19:23.016
So they're labeled with their red.

329
00:19:23.836 --> 00:19:25.496
And we co-cultured these two cells.

330
00:19:25.536 --> 00:19:29.406
We added these two drugs, doxycycline and auxin, to trigger the missegregation of

331
00:19:29.436 --> 00:19:32.626
the Y chromosome into micronuclei, specifically in the male

332
00:19:32.736 --> 00:19:36.456
cells. And what we had hoped for is that then this fragment or the chromosome would

333
00:19:36.476 --> 00:19:39.376
then transfer over to this female recipient cell.

334
00:19:39.396 --> 00:19:43.116
So we then co-selected these cells with two different antibiotics, one

335
00:19:43.156 --> 00:19:46.836
encoded from the male donor cell, one encoded by the female recipient cell.

336
00:19:47.276 --> 00:19:50.616
And in the end, we're left with surviving cells that are comprised of

337
00:19:51.336 --> 00:19:52.576
several different possibilities.

338
00:19:52.956 --> 00:19:56.356
The first are green male cells that became spontaneously resistant to

339
00:19:56.736 --> 00:19:58.636
this selection marker in the female cells.

340
00:19:58.996 --> 00:20:01.966
This actually doesn't really happen, so we'll just ignore that.

341
00:20:02.896 --> 00:20:05.056
The next possibility are these red and green cells.

342
00:20:05.076 --> 00:20:08.395
So these actually represent male-to-female cell-cell fusion events,

343
00:20:09.256 --> 00:20:12.956
which is sort of predicted if you co-select cells and force them to

344
00:20:12.996 --> 00:20:16.695
survive. And then the third possibility are these mCherry positive cells.

345
00:20:16.736 --> 00:20:20.686
So these are female recipient cells that had now became resistant

346
00:20:20.686 --> 00:20:24.536
to the gene that was encoded on the Y chromosome in the male cells.

347
00:20:25.156 --> 00:20:28.836
And so when we do this and look at the cell populations by flow cytometry, we can

348
00:20:28.896 --> 00:20:32.836
see that under control conditions without induction of Y chromosome micronuclei,

349
00:20:33.176 --> 00:20:36.576
most of these events give rise to these cell-cell fusion events as we had

350
00:20:36.616 --> 00:20:39.976
expected. However, if we now induce Y chromosome-specific

351
00:20:39.996 --> 00:20:43.856
micronuclei, this actually shifts from cell-cell fusion events to favor a

352
00:20:43.916 --> 00:20:47.536
lot more of these mCherry labeled cells that now became resistant.

353
00:20:47.826 --> 00:20:49.836
And this is the quantification down here.

354
00:20:50.286 --> 00:20:52.876
And importantly, when we look at the different

355
00:20:53.576 --> 00:20:57.416
mitotic chromosomes from all of these different control conditions,

356
00:20:58.356 --> 00:21:01.816
almost all of them showed evidence of genome doubling between the

357
00:21:02.216 --> 00:21:04.216
male donor and the female recipient genomes.

358
00:21:04.536 --> 00:21:07.516
So they essentially became "tetraploid."

359
00:21:08.396 --> 00:21:12.056
And we also see a small fraction of this in that population of cells in which we

360
00:21:12.076 --> 00:21:15.046
expect the transfer to occur. But importantly, we also see this

361
00:21:15.356 --> 00:21:19.096
subpopulation here that has a chromosome content that matches exactly

362
00:21:19.196 --> 00:21:21.796
that of the female recipient genome.

363
00:21:21.836 --> 00:21:22.946
And so we suspect that these

364
00:21:24.116 --> 00:21:28.016
cells now harbor fragments of the Y chromosome, encoded neomycin

365
00:21:28.056 --> 00:21:31.896
resistance gene, and then these female recipient cells that had taken up that

366
00:21:31.936 --> 00:21:35.716
DNA became resistant to this drug, suggesting that they have now

367
00:21:36.076 --> 00:21:38.836
this new function after inheriting this piece of DNA.

368
00:21:40.656 --> 00:21:44.536
And to really look at this in more detail, we looked at these mitotic chromosome

369
00:21:44.576 --> 00:21:47.816
spreads, and we used different types of DNA FISH probes to look for where are these

370
00:21:47.836 --> 00:21:49.876
DNAs now located in the female genome.

371
00:21:50.366 --> 00:21:53.176
And so these are female metaphase chromosomes, and we can see using

372
00:21:53.196 --> 00:21:57.076
different FISH probes as well as these oligo paint

373
00:21:57.116 --> 00:22:00.996
probes, that these transfer DNA fragments now manifest as

374
00:22:01.006 --> 00:22:04.476
a single copy extra chromosomal DNA within these recipient cell

375
00:22:04.556 --> 00:22:05.036
genomes.

376
00:22:07.036 --> 00:22:10.216
And lastly, in order to demonstrate that these fragments indeed are

377
00:22:10.256 --> 00:22:13.576
transcriptionally active in the recipient cell, we performed single-cell RNA

378
00:22:13.596 --> 00:22:17.406
sequencing, and what this really showed us was that among those mCherry

379
00:22:17.516 --> 00:22:21.376
positive cells, there's this distinct cluster of cells that are characterized

380
00:22:21.396 --> 00:22:25.076
by high levels of the neomycin resistance gene and also a

381
00:22:25.136 --> 00:22:29.116
nearby adjacent Y chromosome-encoded gene that's now being expressed in the

382
00:22:29.136 --> 00:22:32.816
female cells. And we know these are female cells because they lack expression of

383
00:22:32.856 --> 00:22:35.056
these male-specific markers,

384
00:22:36.636 --> 00:22:39.476
suggesting that these fragments, once they've transferred over, are fully

385
00:22:39.496 --> 00:22:43.056
functional, transcriptionally active, and can confer a new phenotype to these

386
00:22:43.096 --> 00:22:43.936
recipient cells.

387
00:22:45.436 --> 00:22:47.536
Okay, so here's the current model of this.

388
00:22:47.736 --> 00:22:48.036
So

389
00:22:49.496 --> 00:22:49.876
after

390
00:22:50.696 --> 00:22:54.356
DNA damage or mitotic errors, this can cause the mislocalization of

391
00:22:54.376 --> 00:22:58.336
genomic DNA to the cytoplasm, indicated here by the presence of

392
00:22:58.376 --> 00:23:01.716
this micronucleus. These two cells, they migrate as part of their

393
00:23:01.736 --> 00:23:05.296
normal nature, and then they come together and come into direct contact,

394
00:23:05.676 --> 00:23:08.976
which then initiates the formation of these nanotube connections between the two

395
00:23:09.016 --> 00:23:09.376
cells.

396
00:23:10.246 --> 00:23:13.956
And then the DNA is now able to transport through this nanotube, enter the

397
00:23:13.996 --> 00:23:17.756
recipient cell, and after the next mitosis and even in subsequent cell

398
00:23:17.776 --> 00:23:18.876
divisions, is now

399
00:23:19.716 --> 00:23:23.496
stably maintained within the recipient cell genomes for

400
00:23:23.555 --> 00:23:26.546
months, actually. And when we showed that these

401
00:23:26.596 --> 00:23:30.476
heritable extra chromosomal DNAs are also transcriptionally

402
00:23:30.486 --> 00:23:34.346
active and can confer new cellular functions to this recipient

403
00:23:34.436 --> 00:23:38.286
cell. And so in just the last couple of seconds, I want to talk about why does this

404
00:23:38.376 --> 00:23:41.716
actually matter. So I think if this is correct, which we

405
00:23:42.636 --> 00:23:46.336
are strongly confident that it is, it really challenges the assumption that

406
00:23:46.356 --> 00:23:49.146
somatic genomes evolve as cell-autonomous units.

407
00:23:49.536 --> 00:23:53.016
Instead, we show here that genomic alterations can also arise through

408
00:23:53.076 --> 00:23:54.876
non-cell-autonomous mechanisms,

409
00:23:55.696 --> 00:23:59.456
and that DNA transfer could represent an unrecognized source of somatic

410
00:23:59.516 --> 00:24:03.426
aneuploidy and also megabase scale-sized DNA copy number

411
00:24:03.516 --> 00:24:07.426
alterations. And then transferred DNA fragments can circularize and

412
00:24:07.536 --> 00:24:10.876
become propagated and potentially amplified in the right context

413
00:24:11.516 --> 00:24:12.476
as ecDNA.

414
00:24:13.286 --> 00:24:17.096
And then in the tumor microenvironment, genomically unstable cancer cells could

415
00:24:17.116 --> 00:24:20.696
potentially disseminate or propagate oncogenes or mutations to

416
00:24:20.736 --> 00:24:22.836
nearby neighboring non-cancer cells.

417
00:24:23.616 --> 00:24:26.896
And so these are exciting lines of direction that my laboratory is now

418
00:24:27.356 --> 00:24:28.236
directly pursuing.

419
00:24:29.176 --> 00:24:31.496
Okay, so with that, I would really like to thank the members of my lab.

420
00:24:31.836 --> 00:24:35.756
So Elizabeth Murray is a graduate student who primarily drove

421
00:24:35.796 --> 00:24:39.256
this work. We have a number of outstanding collaborators from researchers across

422
00:24:39.276 --> 00:24:42.236
the world, as well as our sources of funding. And thank you very much.

423
00:24:46.716 --> 00:24:48.976
Thank

424
00:24:48.996 --> 00:24:52.356
you, Peter.

425
00:24:52.876 --> 00:24:53.366
Any questions?

426
00:24:54.676 --> 00:24:55.575
Raul? Yeah.

427
00:24:55.616 --> 00:24:57.836
Hey, Peter. Great work. Really interesting.

428
00:24:57.916 --> 00:25:01.816
Have you thought about how we could quantify the rate

429
00:25:01.856 --> 00:25:04.946
at which this process might happen in

430
00:25:05.676 --> 00:25:08.226
human samples, in particular human tumor samples?

431
00:25:08.616 --> 00:25:11.636
Like, are there technologies or approaches you can think of?

432
00:25:12.016 --> 00:25:12.356
Because it's-

433
00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:16.940
One question I would have is that a random piece of DNA wouldn't really have

434
00:25:16.980 --> 00:25:20.760
much function, right? So it would only matter if the DNA had an actual

435
00:25:20.840 --> 00:25:24.210
gene or something on it. So how do you think we could quantify-

436
00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:24.450
Right

437
00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:25.840
... the rate?

438
00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:27.360
Yeah. That's a fantastic question.

439
00:25:27.380 --> 00:25:31.230
So I think, most of the DNA transfer events probably does

440
00:25:31.320 --> 00:25:34.170
happen at a low frequency, and it doesn't give rise to much because

441
00:25:35.060 --> 00:25:37.540
depending on what sequences are transferred.

442
00:25:37.560 --> 00:25:40.900
But I think in the right context, so for example, if the right mutation

443
00:25:40.940 --> 00:25:44.140
transfers to another cell, then that could potentially then become

444
00:25:44.180 --> 00:25:47.590
propagated in the presence of a positive selection.

445
00:25:47.990 --> 00:25:51.740
And how can we quantify this? So this is something that my lab has been thinking

446
00:25:51.810 --> 00:25:55.680
about really hard. We haven't come up with a really concrete way to do this yet,

447
00:25:55.700 --> 00:25:59.470
because one of the main challenges is that if you're thinking about an individual

448
00:25:59.500 --> 00:26:02.870
tumor, they essentially share the same SNPs.

449
00:26:03.340 --> 00:26:06.920
So it's really difficult to distinguish between donor-derived DNA

450
00:26:06.980 --> 00:26:09.700
versus recipient cell DNA, right?

451
00:26:10.030 --> 00:26:13.620
And so now we're thinking about different ways where we can experimentally model

452
00:26:13.680 --> 00:26:17.520
this and use sequences that are more amenable to tracking

453
00:26:17.580 --> 00:26:21.330
in the laboratory. And then in the context of actually measuring this

454
00:26:21.360 --> 00:26:24.120
directly in tumors, we're still thinking about that.

455
00:26:24.180 --> 00:26:27.940
But I think it really will rely on new computational techniques to

456
00:26:27.960 --> 00:26:29.840
discriminate between these types of events.

457
00:26:30.270 --> 00:26:33.820
And one way we've been thinking about it is by tracking mutations

458
00:26:33.840 --> 00:26:37.830
between clones or actually DNA copy number alterations between clones

459
00:26:37.860 --> 00:26:41.660
that arise at different times within the same tumor, and using that to infer

460
00:26:41.720 --> 00:26:42.300
whether it was

461
00:26:43.180 --> 00:26:45.320
transferred or not. But that's a really good question.

462
00:26:45.540 --> 00:26:48.340
I don't have the best solid answer at this moment, though.

463
00:26:49.060 --> 00:26:51.620
Peter, quick suggestion. Have you thought about

464
00:26:52.780 --> 00:26:55.860
the context of leukemias? There are hematopoietic stem cell transplantations

465
00:26:55.900 --> 00:26:57.100
happening. Have you thought about-

466
00:26:57.200 --> 00:26:57.210
Absolutely

467
00:26:57.210 --> 00:27:00.560
... looking at samples of those and to see if leukemia cells from the host

468
00:27:01.420 --> 00:27:03.140
and the grafts could be exchanged?

469
00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:06.540
Yeah, absolutely. So one really good example of that are, for example, Fanconi

470
00:27:06.580 --> 00:27:08.020
anemia patients who had undergone

471
00:27:10.180 --> 00:27:13.860
blood transplantations, where you could potentially look for donor-derived

472
00:27:14.140 --> 00:27:17.640
DNA sequences and SNPs present in the donor DNA but not in the

473
00:27:18.820 --> 00:27:22.260
patient DNA. So that's an excellent suggestion.

474
00:27:22.300 --> 00:27:23.279
One more question.

475
00:27:24.040 --> 00:27:24.320
Question.

476
00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:27.580
Sure.

477
00:27:28.680 --> 00:27:31.420
Peter, great talk, and it's an amazing discovery.

478
00:27:32.400 --> 00:27:36.320
So in each case, is DNA damage required

479
00:27:36.380 --> 00:27:40.060
in order to induce this transfer? And in that case, do you think that we're

480
00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:43.540
accelerating this process when we treat patients with

481
00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:47.420
chemotherapy and potentially provoking secondary malignancies?

482
00:27:48.360 --> 00:27:51.980
Absolutely. So in the normal context, the genomic DNA is

483
00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.760
confined to the nucleus. So it's protected from being

484
00:27:55.820 --> 00:27:59.569
transferred. But if you have now DNA that's mislocalized in the cytoplasm, for

485
00:27:59.600 --> 00:28:03.380
example, after DNA damage, after mitotic errors, now it's an

486
00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:06.880
environment where it could then be permissive for undergoing

487
00:28:06.960 --> 00:28:07.440
transfer.

488
00:28:08.420 --> 00:28:11.880
And the question you're asking about whether we're inducing these events with

489
00:28:11.940 --> 00:28:15.900
chemotherapy is something that we're actually trying to test right now in the

490
00:28:16.020 --> 00:28:19.920
laboratory. So we're trying to determine whether DNA transfer occurs in

491
00:28:19.980 --> 00:28:23.860
vivo if you hit tumor cells with either chemotherapy

492
00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:25.440
or radiotherapy. Yeah.

493
00:28:26.860 --> 00:28:28.450
One last question. Howard, do you want to ask something?

494
00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.640
Peter, great talk. My question is whether you think the recipient

495
00:28:32.780 --> 00:28:36.720
cell would have its cGAS-STING pathway activated and therefore

496
00:28:37.100 --> 00:28:39.260
essentially reject the transferred DNA.

497
00:28:40.080 --> 00:28:43.840
And if so, then is this mechanism really restricted to just transfer between

498
00:28:43.880 --> 00:28:44.520
tumor cells?

499
00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:48.980
Yeah. Excellent question. So we don't have direct experimental evidence for

500
00:28:49.020 --> 00:28:52.980
it, but we do think that once it transfers into the recipient cell,

501
00:28:53.140 --> 00:28:55.680
it could then potentially activate the cGAS-STING pathway.

502
00:28:56.840 --> 00:29:00.020
However, we do show that both lamin-containing and

503
00:29:00.440 --> 00:29:02.980
non-lamin-containing DNAs both transfer.

504
00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:06.810
So whether one activates the pathway more strongly than the other, we don't really

505
00:29:06.820 --> 00:29:07.200
know yet.

506
00:29:08.060 --> 00:29:11.450
But we do think that there are potentially pathways that exist to suppress these

507
00:29:11.450 --> 00:29:15.250
events. So, for example, in addition to DNA sensors, one can

508
00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:19.120
also think about cytoplasmic nucleases that could potentially degrade the

509
00:29:19.140 --> 00:29:22.780
DNA once it transfers, or even in the donor cell before it transfers.

510
00:29:22.880 --> 00:29:26.620
But we're still currently trying to understand what are the molecular

511
00:29:26.800 --> 00:29:30.500
mechanisms that regulate these type of processes in both cancer and

512
00:29:30.540 --> 00:29:32.440
non-cancer settings. Yeah.

513
00:29:32.699 --> 00:29:33.699
Peter, fantastic talk.

514
00:29:33.840 --> 00:29:34.060
Thank you.

515
00:29:34.620 --> 00:29:36.780
I'll hand over to Howard Chang now with the next talk.

516
00:29:45.560 --> 00:29:47.120
Thank you, Anton. Good afternoon.

517
00:29:47.220 --> 00:29:50.660
I'm delighted to be here and share some of the progress from our laboratory.

518
00:29:51.820 --> 00:29:53.020
May I have my first slide, please?

519
00:29:57.980 --> 00:29:59.680
Okay. These are my disclosures.

520
00:30:02.620 --> 00:30:06.360
Cancer patients really face a daunting challenge when the cancers contain

521
00:30:06.420 --> 00:30:09.920
extrachromosomal DNA. As you've heard, these are really prevalent

522
00:30:09.980 --> 00:30:13.620
problems that affect both adults and children, men and women.

523
00:30:14.420 --> 00:30:18.020
These are, as we've described, large circular pieces of

524
00:30:18.060 --> 00:30:21.780
DNA that encode oncogenes, regulatory elements, and additional

525
00:30:21.880 --> 00:30:25.280
elements. They are large in the sense that they are 100 kb to a

526
00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:25.940
megabase.

527
00:30:26.760 --> 00:30:30.480
But what I want to talk to you today is really on three important

528
00:30:30.540 --> 00:30:34.200
advances. First, our increasing understanding of how

529
00:30:34.260 --> 00:30:37.720
oncogenes gain a transcriptional advantage on ecDNAs.

530
00:30:38.540 --> 00:30:39.000
Secondly,

531
00:30:39.920 --> 00:30:43.480
how ecDNAs allow rapid genome change, yet retain

532
00:30:43.490 --> 00:30:47.120
the capacity to be passed on through multiple

533
00:30:47.220 --> 00:30:49.020
somatic generations in the cancer cell.

534
00:30:49.700 --> 00:30:52.710
And finally, how this kind of unusual mechanism of

535
00:30:52.780 --> 00:30:56.600
inheritance allows us to identify ecDNAs and their

536
00:30:56.660 --> 00:30:59.790
unique roles in cancer and to improve cancer

537
00:30:59.880 --> 00:31:03.680
diagnostic. And of course, this is a therapeutic vulnerability that we hope to

538
00:31:03.720 --> 00:31:07.510
exploit on top of, because they're not found in normal cells.

539
00:31:08.380 --> 00:31:12.260
All right, so let's dig in. As we start studying extrachromosomal DNA,

540
00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:16.080
one of the first really, I think, surprising and beautiful

541
00:31:16.460 --> 00:31:19.140
discoveries is that they congregate in these dynamic hubs.

542
00:31:19.600 --> 00:31:23.440
When you hear about ecDNAs existing in 10 or maybe even 100

543
00:31:23.500 --> 00:31:27.000
copies in a cancer cell-They don't actually show up in

544
00:31:27.040 --> 00:31:30.840
100 separate dots. We discovered, and we and others, that in

545
00:31:30.900 --> 00:31:34.560
fact they often concentrate into these micron size hubs

546
00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:38.970
where dozens or more ecDNAs come into close physical proximity.

547
00:31:39.790 --> 00:31:43.560
They're held together by specific proteins such as transcriptional machinery,

548
00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:48.360
co-activators such as BRD4, and that if you block

549
00:31:48.420 --> 00:31:52.400
the roles of these proteins, that ecDNAs fly apart, and in

550
00:31:52.460 --> 00:31:55.120
fact, their transcriptional advantage stops.

551
00:31:56.040 --> 00:32:00.000
So this led to a view that these extrachromosomal DNA hubs are

552
00:32:00.040 --> 00:32:03.920
the unit of oncogene function. And what we learned is that inside

553
00:32:03.960 --> 00:32:07.900
these ecDNA hubs, there is a new mode of transcription called

554
00:32:07.960 --> 00:32:10.220
intermolecular gene activation.

555
00:32:10.920 --> 00:32:14.660
So normally in a long piece of chromosome, you have genes and your

556
00:32:14.720 --> 00:32:16.880
DNA regulatory elements on the same molecule.

557
00:32:17.480 --> 00:32:20.940
And these regulatory elements are the switches that decide when and where these

558
00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:24.940
genes turn on and off. And the switches only from near proximity on the

559
00:32:25.020 --> 00:32:27.060
same molecule can turn on the gene.

560
00:32:27.820 --> 00:32:31.320
That inside this ecDNA hub, we can actually have

561
00:32:32.180 --> 00:32:35.300
different molecules, where the enhancer from one

562
00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:39.300
ecDNA actually turns on the gene, the coding sequence, of

563
00:32:39.340 --> 00:32:43.250
a different ecDNA. And these ecDNAs can actually originally come from

564
00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:45.130
different chromosomes. All right?

565
00:32:45.300 --> 00:32:49.280
So basically, this allows a cooperative and combinatorial modes of gene

566
00:32:49.400 --> 00:32:52.840
activation. These ecDNAs gain access to

567
00:32:52.880 --> 00:32:56.500
enhancers that could normally never get at before, and thus

568
00:32:56.580 --> 00:32:58.370
allows this massive transcription.

569
00:32:59.440 --> 00:33:00.990
But this has additional consequences.

570
00:33:01.840 --> 00:33:04.910
And that is that we believe that this will lead to potentially oncogene

571
00:33:05.020 --> 00:33:08.860
diversification in several ways, as I'll show you, because of this kind of

572
00:33:08.880 --> 00:33:12.520
interdependency, and this is, of course, another therapeutic target.

573
00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:17.800
One of the first most direct examples is when we first had the ability

574
00:33:17.820 --> 00:33:21.490
to isolate individual ecDNAs biochemically and

575
00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:24.170
subject them to single molecule or long-read sequencing.

576
00:33:24.830 --> 00:33:28.480
And we can see that in fact there's far more sequence diversity

577
00:33:28.540 --> 00:33:29.600
among ecDNAs.

578
00:33:30.940 --> 00:33:34.549
We oftentimes imagine ecDNAs as a full locus amplification, just a

579
00:33:34.940 --> 00:33:38.620
gene, all its regulatory elements, and in pressing lots of copies, and we

580
00:33:38.660 --> 00:33:39.340
definitely see that.

581
00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:43.630
We also often see what is called enhancer hijacking.

582
00:33:44.140 --> 00:33:48.020
Rearrangements that bring in another enhancer into proximity to

583
00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:51.020
an ecDNA, allowing, let's say, more potent expression.

584
00:33:52.040 --> 00:33:55.160
But we were surprised to see another phenomenon called ecDNA

585
00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:59.100
specialization. This is a situation where you have a coding

586
00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:02.420
sequence that's amplified, but no regulatory elements.

587
00:34:03.020 --> 00:34:06.920
And other times you see focal enhancer amplification, but no

588
00:34:06.960 --> 00:34:07.760
coding sequence.

589
00:34:08.720 --> 00:34:12.341
Now, if you're making an expression construct in the lab and you ended up with

590
00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:16.330
these kinds of results, you probably go back and try to make it again because

591
00:34:16.330 --> 00:34:20.080
the dogma of molecular biology tells us that you wouldn't get gene expression.

592
00:34:20.100 --> 00:34:23.841
But in fact, we see this in fact in patient samples and amplified to

593
00:34:23.900 --> 00:34:25.980
quite high levels, as seen in the

594
00:34:26.980 --> 00:34:30.870
TRACERx or the Genomes England dataset pioneered by

595
00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:32.600
Chris Bailey and Charlie Swanson.

596
00:34:33.160 --> 00:34:37.040
So we interpret this to really mean that there's intermolecular

597
00:34:37.140 --> 00:34:40.520
complementation in the ecDNA hubs because these

598
00:34:40.560 --> 00:34:44.170
enhancers can turn on these coding gene only sequences,

599
00:34:44.500 --> 00:34:48.160
and therefore these kind of unique molecular species can

600
00:34:48.220 --> 00:34:51.560
exist and be possibly selected for in cancer cells.

601
00:34:52.400 --> 00:34:52.620
Okay.

602
00:34:53.801 --> 00:34:57.660
Another really striking observation came from the work of Hyrum Yee, who's in the

603
00:34:57.740 --> 00:35:01.600
audience, and that is the finding that ecDNAs have become a platform

604
00:35:01.620 --> 00:35:03.740
for gene innovation through gene fusions.

605
00:35:04.460 --> 00:35:08.420
We heard this morning about the advent of Gleevec targeting Philadelphia

606
00:35:08.500 --> 00:35:12.320
chromosome, and that, of course, is targeting a gene rearrangement,

607
00:35:12.760 --> 00:35:16.580
a fusion protein, BCR-ABL, now that happens on a chromosome.

608
00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:21.120
And so in this work, pioneered by Hyrum and Shu Zheng, and together with Paul

609
00:35:21.160 --> 00:35:24.650
Michiel, we found that in fact there's a very high rate of

610
00:35:24.720 --> 00:35:28.630
structural variation on extrachromosomal DNAs, and that actually will lead

611
00:35:28.660 --> 00:35:29.600
to gene fusions.

612
00:35:30.540 --> 00:35:34.300
And so this is basically a single coding transcript that will now bring different

613
00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:37.940
kind of elements together. They're actually, in fact, the most

614
00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:41.939
prevalent form of sort of source of structural variants or gene

615
00:35:41.980 --> 00:35:45.800
fusions in solid tumors. And one of the most prevalent one that we found

616
00:35:45.860 --> 00:35:49.300
is one that combines the five prime N exon

617
00:35:49.460 --> 00:35:53.320
one of a long non-coding RNA called PVT1 with

618
00:35:53.560 --> 00:35:56.400
diverse oncogene partners on the three prime N.

619
00:35:56.980 --> 00:35:59.300
And this has the consequence of increasing the

620
00:36:00.380 --> 00:36:04.100
messenger RNA stability of any transcript

621
00:36:04.200 --> 00:36:07.980
that's fused to this PVT1, so for example, MYC, a short-lived transcript,

622
00:36:08.260 --> 00:36:09.980
and that enhances oncogene function.

623
00:36:10.320 --> 00:36:13.380
And that there are actually many other sort of oncogenes that can be boosted in

624
00:36:13.420 --> 00:36:16.500
this way. So think of the PVT1 exon one as a

625
00:36:16.600 --> 00:36:20.400
universal five-prime UTR that basically enhances your RNA

626
00:36:20.460 --> 00:36:21.380
stability.

627
00:36:22.340 --> 00:36:25.000
So we think this is going to be a fruitful area of investigation.

628
00:36:25.760 --> 00:36:29.300
And to summarize the concept, there's this fearsome Greek

629
00:36:29.640 --> 00:36:33.060
monster, right? The mythology, the Chimera, that combines

630
00:36:33.100 --> 00:36:33.710
these

631
00:36:34.840 --> 00:36:38.620
monsters' different capabilities, and that's kind of what the ecDNA provides.

632
00:36:38.660 --> 00:36:42.259
It's a platform for making these now altered transcripts with

633
00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:44.440
enhanced molecular capabilities. Dr.

634
00:36:44.660 --> 00:36:48.510
Hyrum Yee, who's in the audience, will be giving a talk on this topic in the

635
00:36:48.540 --> 00:36:50.699
mini symposium tomorrow afternoon.

636
00:36:50.740 --> 00:36:53.540
So please go check it out if you find this interesting.

637
00:36:55.420 --> 00:36:55.520
The

638
00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:01.020
second major challenge I think ecDNA faces is its mitotic

639
00:37:01.030 --> 00:37:04.220
transmission. As Anton and Peter both described,

640
00:37:04.260 --> 00:37:08.220
ecDNAs lack centromeres. And so you can imagine that with

641
00:37:08.280 --> 00:37:12.250
every cell division, this is a mortal challenge to its

642
00:37:12.380 --> 00:37:15.770
propagation. And what we've learned, we and others have seen for

643
00:37:15.920 --> 00:37:19.780
decades, is that extrachromosomal DNAs, in this case labeled in green,

644
00:37:20.280 --> 00:37:24.040
will basically attach to mitotic chromosomes labeled in purple here.

645
00:37:24.380 --> 00:37:28.120
And as the chromosome segregates, the ecDNA basically will hitch a ride

646
00:37:28.200 --> 00:37:29.860
into the resulting daughter cells.

647
00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:34.252
This is called mitotic hitchhiking.This is a phenomenon that also

648
00:37:34.292 --> 00:37:37.852
is seen with DNA viruses that don't have centromeres.

649
00:37:38.192 --> 00:37:41.492
But the question is, how does this happen? What is the molecular mechanism?

650
00:37:41.992 --> 00:37:45.892
So we imagine that there must be some sort of special sequence that allows

651
00:37:45.932 --> 00:37:49.652
ecDNAs and a machinery to attach to mitotic chromosomes.

652
00:37:50.492 --> 00:37:52.222
So two very talented graduate students,

653
00:37:53.432 --> 00:37:57.232
Venkat Sankar and King Hong, devised this new strategy that we call

654
00:37:57.312 --> 00:38:00.752
Retain-seq to identify potential retention elements.

655
00:38:01.312 --> 00:38:04.272
This strategy starts by taking human genomic DNA,

656
00:38:04.812 --> 00:38:08.212
fragmenting them into small pieces, and including them into

657
00:38:08.392 --> 00:38:10.672
a heterologous plasmid

658
00:38:11.632 --> 00:38:15.612
and asking, would any of these sequences allow this plasmid,

659
00:38:15.672 --> 00:38:18.912
upon transfection in multiple passages, to be

660
00:38:18.972 --> 00:38:22.092
retained and therefore, basically,

661
00:38:22.592 --> 00:38:24.772
proportionally amplified over time.

662
00:38:24.832 --> 00:38:28.372
Okay, so then when you sequence this in the DNA, the input

663
00:38:28.412 --> 00:38:32.172
genome-specific sequences might be retained and therefore elevated.

664
00:38:32.202 --> 00:38:34.212
And this strategy proved successful.

665
00:38:34.252 --> 00:38:37.852
It's an unbiased approach, and we discover a family of

666
00:38:37.951 --> 00:38:40.792
actually thousands of these retention elements that are present on

667
00:38:40.832 --> 00:38:44.792
ecDNAs. And this is an example showing that, in fact, their mechanism

668
00:38:44.852 --> 00:38:48.172
is by enhancing retention. So we have these

669
00:38:48.492 --> 00:38:52.412
cells where we have basically lacO array to allow imaging of the

670
00:38:52.432 --> 00:38:56.232
ecDNA. We can have it in a naked fashion or add the retention

671
00:38:56.312 --> 00:38:58.292
element. And if you transfect

672
00:39:00.012 --> 00:39:03.932
the plasmid, we can then watch over time by labeling the

673
00:39:03.952 --> 00:39:07.472
lacO with associated proteins, whether these ecDNAs are

674
00:39:07.512 --> 00:39:11.352
basically attached to the mitotic chromosomes or perhaps are actually

675
00:39:11.392 --> 00:39:13.532
detached if they lack the retention elements.

676
00:39:14.032 --> 00:39:17.872
And what we found is that a single retention element basically

677
00:39:18.412 --> 00:39:19.972
halves the rate of failure. Right?

678
00:39:20.052 --> 00:39:23.212
So basically increase your chance for retention by at least 50%.

679
00:39:23.852 --> 00:39:27.732
And this can be imaged basically through the entire time

680
00:39:27.812 --> 00:39:31.392
through mitosis. And this is a endogenous ecDNA.

681
00:39:31.702 --> 00:39:34.612
And what we also learned is that having multiple retention elements

682
00:39:35.312 --> 00:39:38.612
sequentially improves the efficacy to over 95%.

683
00:39:38.972 --> 00:39:41.751
And so this will have a very significant potential impact.

684
00:39:42.812 --> 00:39:46.572
Okay. We also went in and delved into the molecular mechanism

685
00:39:46.692 --> 00:39:50.332
of what are these sequences and where do they attach to.

686
00:39:50.352 --> 00:39:53.972
And this then involves using a classic technology that's called chromosome

687
00:39:54.032 --> 00:39:58.011
confirmation capture or Hi-C to map the contact points between the

688
00:39:58.032 --> 00:40:00.761
retention elements and their chromosomal anchoring sites.

689
00:40:01.342 --> 00:40:04.922
What we learned is that there's actually a very interesting logic to this

690
00:40:04.932 --> 00:40:08.642
retention, and that is that these retention elements comprise of

691
00:40:08.772 --> 00:40:12.372
specific classes of promoters, gene promoters that

692
00:40:12.392 --> 00:40:16.132
allow transcription. And these bookmark sites, that's the places where the

693
00:40:16.172 --> 00:40:18.932
ecDNA is attached to, are actually enhancers

694
00:40:19.272 --> 00:40:22.952
where they interact. So in a

695
00:40:22.992 --> 00:40:26.972
way, these mitotic retention, right, recapitulates

696
00:40:27.032 --> 00:40:30.972
enhancer-promoter contact that happens in normal chromosome gene

697
00:40:30.981 --> 00:40:34.912
expression, except this happens in interphase and mitotic

698
00:40:34.932 --> 00:40:38.332
retention happens in M phase. Moreover, there's something very

699
00:40:38.342 --> 00:40:40.312
special. It is not that

700
00:40:41.352 --> 00:40:45.312
every promoter enhancer can be a retention element, but that

701
00:40:45.672 --> 00:40:49.132
there are specific sites in the genome that

702
00:40:49.172 --> 00:40:51.232
retain their accessibility and activity.

703
00:40:51.612 --> 00:40:55.452
So during mitosis, their chromosomes condense 10,000-fold, but

704
00:40:55.552 --> 00:40:58.481
only a special subset of sites retain accessibility.

705
00:40:58.872 --> 00:41:00.632
So this is called mitotic bookmarking.

706
00:41:01.012 --> 00:41:04.972
So these mitotic bookmark sites are massively enriched, 150-fold

707
00:41:05.012 --> 00:41:06.792
plus enriched as retention elements.

708
00:41:07.172 --> 00:41:11.132
So we understand that this retention activity is hacking

709
00:41:11.212 --> 00:41:14.932
into exploiting this endogenous mechanism of mitotic

710
00:41:14.952 --> 00:41:18.622
bookmarking, which allows gene transcription memory to get

711
00:41:18.652 --> 00:41:20.452
reactivated in the next cell cycle.

712
00:41:20.812 --> 00:41:24.672
And this is the mechanism that these cells are hacking into.

713
00:41:25.612 --> 00:41:25.932
Okay.

714
00:41:27.992 --> 00:41:31.882
And finally, we performed mathematic modeling led by

715
00:41:31.912 --> 00:41:35.012
Matt Jones to ask how important are these retention elements.

716
00:41:35.032 --> 00:41:38.842
And so if you take, for example, ecDNAs with

717
00:41:38.872 --> 00:41:42.072
very a potent selection factor, let's say a potent oncogene.

718
00:41:42.452 --> 00:41:44.972
We can imagine that they would really confer cell growth.

719
00:41:45.272 --> 00:41:49.171
