957
00:56:01.076 --> 00:56:04.876
how this happens, and what contributes to this detachment, and what the

958
00:56:04.916 --> 00:56:08.876
consequences are, most importantly, for the cells that inherit such micronuclei.

959
00:56:11.806 --> 00:56:15.496
So in order to understand this better, Lotte Brückner in my lab, a very talented

960
00:56:15.536 --> 00:56:19.216
PhD student, studied isogenic cell line pairs in which

961
00:56:20.416 --> 00:56:22.936
an oncogene, such as MYC, EGFR, or MYC--

962
00:56:24.036 --> 00:56:24.946
sorry. MYC, yeah,

963
00:56:25.936 --> 00:56:29.236
are amplified either in a linear form in an HSR or

964
00:56:29.276 --> 00:56:33.196
extrachromosomally. These are derived from different cancer entities, and

965
00:56:33.236 --> 00:56:36.156
she asked the question, how often do we see such

966
00:56:36.216 --> 00:56:39.316
amplicons outside the nucleus within a micronucleus?

967
00:56:41.676 --> 00:56:44.856
And here on the right side, you can see that with regards to those

968
00:56:45.056 --> 00:56:49.036
micronuclei that did not contain the amplicon, there was no difference to be

969
00:56:49.096 --> 00:56:52.376
seen between cells with a linear or extrachromosomal amplification.

970
00:56:52.436 --> 00:56:56.346
Suggesting that in general, chromosomal instability does not seem to be different

971
00:56:56.356 --> 00:56:59.876
between those two cell types. But when looking at those

972
00:56:59.916 --> 00:57:03.696
micronuclei that contain the amplicon sequence specifically, we could see a

973
00:57:03.735 --> 00:57:07.256
significantly higher degree of micronucleation in those cells with ecDNA,

974
00:57:07.336 --> 00:57:11.176
suggesting that there is some likelihood of ecDNA

975
00:57:11.256 --> 00:57:15.196
hitchhiking to not work, and those ecDNA ending up

976
00:57:15.256 --> 00:57:18.996
in micronuclei. But what I would like you to pay attention to

977
00:57:19.316 --> 00:57:22.676
is that there's actually quite a lot of variability between different cell types

978
00:57:23.176 --> 00:57:26.816
in the amount of those micronuclei suggesting that

979
00:57:26.876 --> 00:57:30.196
retention capacity might be different between different cell types, and this will

980
00:57:30.236 --> 00:57:32.246
be more important at the end of this talk.

981
00:57:34.876 --> 00:57:38.306
So in order to understand whether the mere presence of ecDNA would

982
00:57:38.316 --> 00:57:38.876
promote

983
00:57:39.876 --> 00:57:43.416
the likelihood of their micronucleation, we teamed up with Andrea

984
00:57:43.456 --> 00:57:47.436
Ventura, a part of our E-Dynamics Cancer Grand Challenges consortium at Sloan

985
00:57:47.496 --> 00:57:51.396
Kettering, who has developed a really elegant model in which you can engineer

986
00:57:51.476 --> 00:57:53.676
ecDNA using the Cre-Lox system.

987
00:57:54.556 --> 00:57:58.116
And so he engineered mouse cells that either had MYC on

988
00:57:58.136 --> 00:58:01.316
ecDNA or where MYC was expressed from a linear transgene.

989
00:58:01.666 --> 00:58:05.256
And you can clearly see on the right side that only in the presence of an

990
00:58:05.596 --> 00:58:06.356
MYC ecDNA,

991
00:58:07.176 --> 00:58:10.216
we detect high degrees of micronucleation.

992
00:58:10.316 --> 00:58:14.296
Again, suggesting that it's not just the expression level of the oncogene or

993
00:58:14.816 --> 00:58:18.316
some sort of chromosomal instability, but the ecDNA

994
00:58:18.326 --> 00:58:19.076
itself that

995
00:58:20.276 --> 00:58:21.536
promotes this micronucleation.

996
00:58:22.856 --> 00:58:25.716
Based on this, we thought that this was a stochastic process, and that just

997
00:58:26.436 --> 00:58:29.876
randomly one or two ecDNA might fail to tether, might fail to be

998
00:58:29.916 --> 00:58:33.156
retained as how it showed and would end up in a micronucleus.

999
00:58:33.736 --> 00:58:36.756
But when using a system that was developed in Paul Michel's lab, where you can

1000
00:58:36.836 --> 00:58:38.976
track ecDNA using

1001
00:58:39.796 --> 00:58:43.476
fluorescence imaging, where the ecDNA contains a Tet-O array and

1002
00:58:43.536 --> 00:58:47.476
TetR mNeonGreen would label those ecDNA specifically, we observed something

1003
00:58:47.536 --> 00:58:47.976
interesting.

1004
00:58:49.116 --> 00:58:52.956
We saw that when ecDNA detached, they tended to form clusters of

1005
00:58:52.996 --> 00:58:56.896
ecDNA, and those clusters were inherited on average in one of the two

1006
00:58:56.956 --> 00:59:00.936
daughter cells and not both, and in one large micronucleus.

1007
00:59:00.996 --> 00:59:04.666
Suggesting that this process was asymmetric and was originating mostly from

1008
00:59:04.736 --> 00:59:05.876
clusters of ecDNA,

1009
00:59:07.176 --> 00:59:09.956
which suggests that there's a directed process underneath this detachment.

1010
00:59:11.476 --> 00:59:13.296
And this was a little bit reminiscent of

1011
00:59:14.216 --> 00:59:18.036
some of the chromatin fragments that you can see tethered together during

1012
00:59:18.056 --> 00:59:21.916
mitosis, so we asked, are these ecDNA maybe damaged?

1013
00:59:22.026 --> 00:59:25.756
And indeed, when looking for signs of DNA damage, those

1014
00:59:25.816 --> 00:59:27.756
clusters of ecDNA that detached

1015
00:59:29.576 --> 00:59:29.796
showed

1016
00:59:31.216 --> 00:59:32.876
heightened signs of DNA damage.

1017
00:59:34.336 --> 00:59:37.976
And so that has asked the question, well, is DNA damage actually responsible for

1018
00:59:37.996 --> 00:59:41.856
the detachment and clustering? In order to test that, we directed

1019
00:59:41.996 --> 00:59:45.926
CRISPR-Cas9 directly to the ecDNA and induced cuts on

1020
00:59:45.996 --> 00:59:49.656
ecDNA. As you can see here on the left side, this CRISPR guided cuts

1021
00:59:50.976 --> 00:59:54.796
led to the detachment and clustering of ecDNA that was damaged and

1022
00:59:54.856 --> 00:59:58.536
also caused them to micronucleate in one of the daughter cells.

1023
01:00:00.296 --> 01:00:03.826
Which indicates that really, DNA damage on ecDNA can promote that clustering,

1024
01:00:03.896 --> 01:00:05.456
detachment, and micronucleation.

1025
01:00:06.636 --> 01:00:10.336
And similar as seen as for other chromatin fragments that are

1026
01:00:11.116 --> 01:00:15.036
unrepaired in mitosis, which are held together as also Peter Lee

1027
01:00:15.316 --> 01:00:19.255
contributed importantly to by CIP2A, TOPBP1,

1028
01:00:19.315 --> 01:00:23.196
MDC1, those clusters of ecDNA were also associated with this

1029
01:00:23.236 --> 01:00:26.936
complex. And moreover, when disrupting this complex

1030
01:00:27.056 --> 01:00:30.536
through shRNA-mediated knockdown of each of those components, we saw a

1031
01:00:30.616 --> 01:00:33.936
clear dispersal of this cluster into single

1032
01:00:33.976 --> 01:00:37.666
ecDNA that would then form smaller micronuclei in both daughter

1033
01:00:37.696 --> 01:00:38.036
cells.

1034
01:00:39.216 --> 01:00:41.136
Which suggests that this

1035
01:00:41.936 --> 01:00:45.516
complex is really important for the clustering of ecDNA during

1036
01:00:45.536 --> 01:00:46.096
mitosis.

1037
01:00:46.896 --> 01:00:50.336
But what was not clear was whether or not this detachment

1038
01:00:50.436 --> 01:00:53.556
involved damaged chromatin fragments that would

1039
01:00:53.636 --> 01:00:57.276
co-segregate with ecDNA into a micronucleus, whether this was

1040
01:00:57.336 --> 01:01:01.036
only happening to one ecDNA species at a time,

1041
01:01:01.436 --> 01:01:05.416
or whether maybe non-homologous different ecDNA species would collectively go into

1042
01:01:05.426 --> 01:01:06.076
a micronucleus.

1043
01:01:06.916 --> 01:01:10.136
And to address this question, we really needed a new method that would sensitively

1044
01:01:10.176 --> 01:01:13.856
detect and quantify any type of DNA in single

1045
01:01:13.916 --> 01:01:14.656
micronuclei.

1046
01:01:15.556 --> 01:01:19.436
And in order to do this, Robin Xu, a very talented MD-PhD student in the lab,

1047
01:01:19.496 --> 01:01:23.056
developed a method that he termed single micronucleus and main nucleus

1048
01:01:23.096 --> 01:01:26.876
sequencing or MNM-seq, in which we laser

1049
01:01:26.896 --> 01:01:30.776
microdissect out both the micronucleus and the adjacent primary

1050
01:01:30.836 --> 01:01:34.036
nucleus, followed by sequencing and analysis.

1051
01:01:36.336 --> 01:01:40.276
And as you can imagine, this is quite a difficult task to do, but really gave

1052
01:01:40.316 --> 01:01:43.336
us some really interesting insights, not only into ecDNA

1053
01:01:44.196 --> 01:01:47.876
locations into the micronucleus, but also can now help us understand patterns

1054
01:01:47.886 --> 01:01:49.856
of chromosomal instability in general.

1055
01:01:51.316 --> 01:01:54.916
So applying this method to cell lines in which we know that different

1056
01:01:54.956 --> 01:01:56.376
ecDNA species exist,

1057
01:01:57.276 --> 01:01:59.096
Robin observed something quite interesting.

1058
01:01:59.976 --> 01:02:03.896
In the vast majority of cases, those micronuclei only contained

1059
01:02:03.936 --> 01:02:06.816
the ecDNA, and only very rarely that we see any chromatin

1060
01:02:06.916 --> 01:02:10.828
fragments.Not only were these chock-full with

1061
01:02:10.868 --> 01:02:14.428
Ecdna, but we saw that all different Ecdna species found in the

1062
01:02:14.488 --> 01:02:18.148
cell were found in the same micronucleus, suggesting that Ecdna

1063
01:02:18.428 --> 01:02:22.178
collectively might missegregate into micronuclei, which kind of was

1064
01:02:22.228 --> 01:02:22.818
also

1065
01:02:24.208 --> 01:02:27.088
similar to what had been observed in Ecdna hubs.

1066
01:02:30.208 --> 01:02:33.188
So we validated this using FISH. On the left side, you'll see a metaphase spread,

1067
01:02:33.308 --> 01:02:36.548
just to confirm to you that these are really independent, different Ecdna

1068
01:02:36.628 --> 01:02:38.068
structures that exist in the cell.

1069
01:02:38.558 --> 01:02:42.468
And on the right side, you'll see micronuclei that contained

1070
01:02:42.568 --> 01:02:45.548
all different Ecdna species within the same micronucleus.

1071
01:02:46.368 --> 01:02:49.788
And this raised another question, and the question was, well, is it

1072
01:02:49.848 --> 01:02:53.588
maybe that you don't need each Ecdna to be damaged, but maybe one

1073
01:02:53.628 --> 01:02:57.608
Ecdna will drag other Ecdna into the same micronucleus,

1074
01:02:57.628 --> 01:02:59.988
similar to what we see with Ecdna hubs?

1075
01:03:00.708 --> 01:03:04.508
And so one experiment we did to test this was to induce a cut in one

1076
01:03:04.588 --> 01:03:08.368
Ecdna and see what happens to another Ecdna species that's independent.

1077
01:03:09.378 --> 01:03:12.668
And to our surprise, we saw that this cut on one Ecdna-containing

1078
01:03:12.728 --> 01:03:16.088
MYC led to the co-missegregation of the other Ecdna

1079
01:03:16.688 --> 01:03:19.828
into the same micronucleus, whereas we never saw this

1080
01:03:19.888 --> 01:03:22.388
other Ecdna alone in a micronucleus.

1081
01:03:23.428 --> 01:03:27.168
That really suggests that it's not only the DNA damage, but maybe the signaling

1082
01:03:27.188 --> 01:03:31.108
involved or other factors that cluster Ecdna together that can

1083
01:03:31.168 --> 01:03:34.588
lead to collective Ecdna missegregation into the same micronucleus.

1084
01:03:37.248 --> 01:03:40.748
So to summarize, this new method of MN-seq allowed us to understand

1085
01:03:41.468 --> 01:03:43.208
that Ecdna, when damaged,

1086
01:03:44.788 --> 01:03:48.528
tends to missegregate collectively together with other non-homologous

1087
01:03:48.588 --> 01:03:51.288
sequences and independent of other chromatin fragments.

1088
01:03:52.488 --> 01:03:56.338
And so you may ask yourself now, well, this is all interesting, but how relevant is

1089
01:03:56.368 --> 01:03:57.228
this for the cell?

1090
01:03:58.268 --> 01:04:02.068
So in order to understand that, we went back to the system that was beautifully

1091
01:04:02.128 --> 01:04:05.888
established in Paul Michel's lab, and Aditi in his lab, a very talented

1092
01:04:05.928 --> 01:04:09.318
PhD student, looked at these cells over time and asked,

1093
01:04:09.618 --> 01:04:13.268
"Well, when a cell inherits a micronucleus, what happens to that cell?"

1094
01:04:14.988 --> 01:04:15.878
And what was really

1095
01:04:18.228 --> 01:04:21.708
quite remarkable was to see that those cells that inherited a micronucleus that

1096
01:04:21.748 --> 01:04:25.528
contained a lot of Ecdna behaved quite differently to other cells that either

1097
01:04:25.568 --> 01:04:29.468
didn't have a micronucleus or had a micronucleus of other content, in

1098
01:04:29.508 --> 01:04:33.128
that they stopped dividing, tended to undergo cell death, or

1099
01:04:33.168 --> 01:04:35.148
proliferated at much, much lower extent.

1100
01:04:35.808 --> 01:04:38.688
Which suggests that if Ecdna fails to

1101
01:04:39.588 --> 01:04:43.288
be retained in a cell and leaves the nucleus, this

1102
01:04:43.368 --> 01:04:46.468
has really important implications for cancer cell fitness.

1103
01:04:49.568 --> 01:04:52.868
In order to better understand whether this was also relevant in patients, we

1104
01:04:52.908 --> 01:04:56.808
set out to look for

1105
01:04:56.848 --> 01:05:00.828
micronucleation in different patient populations, all with different types of

1106
01:05:00.868 --> 01:05:02.828
oncogenes amplified on Ecdna,

1107
01:05:03.668 --> 01:05:05.588
to ask, well, how often does this happen there?

1108
01:05:07.228 --> 01:05:10.478
And quite strikingly, what I showed you at the beginning with cell lines, this was

1109
01:05:10.528 --> 01:05:14.298
quite exaggerated in patients. Here we saw on the one hand that there was

1110
01:05:14.328 --> 01:05:18.108
higher micronucleation rate in patients with Ecdna, but

1111
01:05:18.488 --> 01:05:22.148
the variance of micronucleation rate was quite high between different patients.

1112
01:05:22.208 --> 01:05:25.808
Some patients almost behaved like, or cancers behaved like

1113
01:05:25.848 --> 01:05:29.648
cancers without Ecdna, and some had almost no cells that

1114
01:05:29.688 --> 01:05:33.108
didn't have micronucleus with Ecdna, suggesting there was really a huge

1115
01:05:33.168 --> 01:05:37.128
heterogeneity when it comes to the retention capacity or the likelihood of Ecdna

1116
01:05:37.528 --> 01:05:39.588
to be lost from a nucleus in those cancers.

1117
01:05:40.348 --> 01:05:44.328
And that raised the question whether this would impact cancer cell fitness,

1118
01:05:45.368 --> 01:05:47.488
and therefore the cancer aggressiveness in general.

1119
01:05:48.048 --> 01:05:51.708
But in order to address that question, we needed a homogenous population of

1120
01:05:51.828 --> 01:05:55.808
patients that all had the same Ecdna with the same

1121
01:05:55.868 --> 01:05:59.848
oncogene, and for which we had clinical data from diagnosis over

1122
01:05:59.888 --> 01:06:02.808
the course of treatment, and for which we could establish

1123
01:06:02.868 --> 01:06:06.748
the micronucleation tendency at diagnosis prior to

1124
01:06:06.798 --> 01:06:10.588
treatment. So we collected hundreds of neuroblastoma patients for which we

1125
01:06:10.608 --> 01:06:12.048
know that MYCN is the most

1126
01:06:13.008 --> 01:06:16.608
commonly amplified oncogene on Ecdna, and found 86

1127
01:06:16.668 --> 01:06:20.268
patients for which all of those were on Ecdna, and for which

1128
01:06:20.608 --> 01:06:24.448
we knew that all of those got the same standard of care treatment over time,

1129
01:06:24.868 --> 01:06:28.028
and where we had samples at diagnosis prior to any treatment.

1130
01:06:28.938 --> 01:06:30.998
And again, Lotte stratified those into those

1131
01:06:32.528 --> 01:06:36.218
cells with or without micronuclei and asked the question whether

1132
01:06:36.228 --> 01:06:37.828
Ecdna was found within them.

1133
01:06:39.708 --> 01:06:39.898
And

1134
01:06:41.268 --> 01:06:45.228
remarkably, we found that when Ecdna tended to be in the micronucleus

1135
01:06:45.248 --> 01:06:48.868
in those cancers, those patients did much better than

1136
01:06:48.988 --> 01:06:52.808
patients in which either micronuclei were found but didn't contain any

1137
01:06:52.828 --> 01:06:55.768
Ecdna, or those patients without any micronuclei.

1138
01:06:56.848 --> 01:07:00.728
Which really suggests that this cell biological phenomenon that we saw in vitro

1139
01:07:01.368 --> 01:07:05.058
not only translates to impaired cell fitness on a cellular level,

1140
01:07:05.528 --> 01:07:09.028
but seems to also impact the aggressiveness of this tumor

1141
01:07:09.728 --> 01:07:11.708
in patients over time.

1142
01:07:12.608 --> 01:07:15.908
And looking at these Kaplan-Meier curves, this was really addressing one

1143
01:07:15.928 --> 01:07:17.568
fundamental old question that we had in

1144
01:07:18.408 --> 01:07:21.928
the field of neuroblastoma research, which was that all MYCN amplified

1145
01:07:21.948 --> 01:07:24.297
neuroblastomas had been known for decades to

1146
01:07:24.988 --> 01:07:28.658
be very aggressive. And actually, neuroblastoma is one of the first

1147
01:07:28.708 --> 01:07:32.228
entities in which MYCN amplification on Ecdna was used to

1148
01:07:32.308 --> 01:07:35.588
stratify patients because we knew that this was an aggressive phenotype.

1149
01:07:36.648 --> 01:07:39.968
But clinically, we always observed a couple of patients that did better than

1150
01:07:40.048 --> 01:07:43.748
others, and we couldn't find any genetic evidence that would give us a

1151
01:07:43.788 --> 01:07:46.828
stratification of those patients that would perform better under treatment than

1152
01:07:46.888 --> 01:07:49.728
others. And we believe that now, looking at

1153
01:07:49.768 --> 01:07:52.388
Ecdna kind of retention

1154
01:07:53.708 --> 01:07:54.888
or their extranuclear

1155
01:07:55.768 --> 01:07:58.608
existence may help us to stratify those patients.

1156
01:07:59.068 --> 01:08:02.728
But not only that, if you look at those curves, you might imagine that maybe

1157
01:08:03.008 --> 01:08:06.808
we can now devise therapies that would force Ecdna

1158
01:08:07.308 --> 01:08:11.168
to be lost in mitosis, going into micronuclei, and maybe we could

1159
01:08:11.208 --> 01:08:15.018
make those patients behave more like the patients that have a lot of Ecdna in

1160
01:08:15.048 --> 01:08:18.960
micronuclei.So in order to address that question, we

1161
01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:22.800
collaborated with a company called Econic Biosciences which I

1162
01:08:22.840 --> 01:08:26.590
co-founded and is based in London, and found inhibitors that

1163
01:08:26.590 --> 01:08:30.561
would disrupt ecDNA tethering to a great extent, as seen here on the left

1164
01:08:30.601 --> 01:08:34.080
side. We see all this ecDNA detaching from chromosomes.

1165
01:08:34.980 --> 01:08:38.760
And so when we applied this inhibitor to patient-derived xenografts that either had

1166
01:08:38.800 --> 01:08:42.300
the same amplicon amplified on an ecDNA or an

1167
01:08:42.440 --> 01:08:46.380
HSR, same tumor entity, and treated those patient-derived

1168
01:08:46.400 --> 01:08:49.740
xenograft models with this inhibitor, we saw drastic tumor regressions

1169
01:08:50.160 --> 01:08:53.519
only in the context of ecDNA. But in the context of

1170
01:08:53.580 --> 01:08:57.221
intrachromosomal amplifications, this did not seem to change the tumor's

1171
01:08:57.240 --> 01:09:00.641
behavior to the same extent. Which really suggests that

1172
01:09:00.700 --> 01:09:01.280
ecDNA

1173
01:09:02.620 --> 01:09:06.561
retention is a therapeutically actionable liability

1174
01:09:06.940 --> 01:09:10.280
of those cancers, which we think we should exploit more in the future.

1175
01:09:12.820 --> 01:09:16.181
So with this, I'd like to summarize what I talked to you about today, and that is

1176
01:09:16.221 --> 01:09:19.820
that the retention elements and the retention of ecDNA we know is

1177
01:09:19.860 --> 01:09:21.800
important for ecDNA to be immortal.

1178
01:09:21.860 --> 01:09:25.760
But not only that, we also know that if ecDNA is not

1179
01:09:25.800 --> 01:09:29.200
retained and failed to retain, it's not only that they will be lost, as Howard

1180
01:09:29.240 --> 01:09:32.860
showed, but if they're lost and go outside the

1181
01:09:32.920 --> 01:09:36.521
nucleus and go into a micronucleus, this impacts cells'

1182
01:09:36.960 --> 01:09:40.641
fitness in that they divide less, undergo cell death more

1183
01:09:40.700 --> 01:09:44.580
often, and this translates to differences in patient survival, which we think we

1184
01:09:44.620 --> 01:09:45.039
can now

1185
01:09:46.840 --> 01:09:47.740
address therapeutically.

1186
01:09:48.860 --> 01:09:51.900
